{{Infobox artwork | title = Cybele | other_language_1 = | other_title_1 = | other_language_2 = | other_title_2 = | image = Seated Woman (Cybele) sculpture by Rodin; left side.JPG | image_upright = | alt = | image_size = 200px | caption = Cybele sculpture by Rodin; Walking Man in the background | artist = [[Auguste Rodin]] | catalogue = | year = {{start date|1890/1904}} | completion_date = <!-- For a more specific date (post-1583): {{start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} --> | type = Sculpture | material = [[Bronze sculpture|Bronze]] | subject = | height_metric = <!-- (i.e. in metric units) --> | width_metric = | length_metric = | diameter_metric = | height_imperial = <!-- (i.e. in imperial units) --> | width_imperial = | length_imperial = | diameter_imperial = | dimensions = | dimensions_ref = | metric_unit = cm <!-- Note: this parameter must either use the value given or not be included --> | imperial_unit = in <!-- Note: this parameter must either use the value given or not be included --> | condition = | city = [[Houston]], Texas, United States | museum = [[Museum of Fine Arts, Houston]] | accession = | coordinates = <!-- Only use for the coordinates (when known) of the artwork itself, i.e. not for the site, building, structure, etc where it is kept, otherwise leave blank (or omit): {{coord|LAT|LON|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} --> | owner = | preceded_by = <!-- preceding work by the same artist --> | followed_by = <!-- next work by the same artist --> | website = <!-- Official webpage/site only: {{URL|example.com}} --> }}
'''''Cybele''''' is an outdoor [[bronze sculpture]] by French artist [[Auguste Rodin]], installed at the [[Museum of Fine Arts, Houston]]'s [[Lillie and Hugh Roy Cullen Sculpture Garden]], in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Texas]].
==Description== Auguste Rodin's ''Cybele'' was modeled c. 1890, enlarged in 1904, and cast in 1982 as edition 3/8.<ref name=MFAH>{{cite web|title=Inside the MFAH Friday Afternoon Lecture "Auguste Rodin: Father of Modern Sculpture" |url=http://www.mfah.org/calendar/inside-mfah-friday-afternoon-lecture-auguste-rodin/10661/ |publisher=[[Museum of Fine Arts, Houston]] |accessdate=October 27, 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906173746/http://www.mfah.org/calendar/inside-mfah-friday-afternoon-lecture-auguste-rodin/10661/ |archivedate=September 6, 2015 |df= }}</ref> It is on loan from Iris Cantor and the Cantor Foundation on behalf of B. Gerald Cantor.<ref name=MFAH/><ref name=Map>{{cite web|last=Loddeke|first=Leslie|title=New buff sculptures shake up the Houston art scene and create a Paris-like vision: It's Rodin mania!|url=http://houston.culturemap.com/news/arts/09-01-14-new-buff-sculptures-shake-up-the-houston-art-scene-and-create-a-paris-like-scene-its-rodin-mania/|accessdate=October 27, 2015|date=September 1, 2014|publisher=CultureMap Houston}}</ref> The statue depicts the seated "voluptuous" [[Cybele|goddess of the same name]].<ref name=MFAH/><ref name=Map/><ref name=Tommaney>{{cite news|last1=Tommaney|first1=Jim|title=The Hidden Treasure of the Lillie and Hugh Roy Cullen Sculpture Garden|url=http://www.houstonpress.com/arts/the-hidden-treasures-of-the-lillie-and-hugh-roy-cullen-sculpture-garden-6369390|accessdate=October 27, 2015|work=[[Houston Press]]|publisher=[[Voice Media Group]]|date=November 25, 2014}}</ref> It is one of three Rodin sculptures in the garden; the other two are ''[[The Spirit of Eternal Repose]]'' (1898–1899) and ''[[The Walking Man]]'' (1877–1878).<ref name=Tommaney/>
